# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: framer-motion
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:framer-motion/animation] The animation above consists of these six frames repeated indefinitely.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Animation is contrasted with live action, although the two do not exist in isolation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Many filmmakers have produced films that are a hybrid of the two.
[src:framer-motion/animation] As CGI increasingly approximates photographic imagery, filmmakers can relatively easily composite 3D animated visual effects (VFX) into their film, rather than using practical effects.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Computer animation can be very detailed 3D animation, while 2D computer animation (which may have the look of traditional animation) can be used for stylistic reasons, low bandwidth, or faster real-time renderings.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Other common animation methods apply a stop motion technique to two- and three-dimensional objects like paper cutouts, puppets, or clay figures.
[src:framer-motion/animation] An **animated cartoon**, or simply a **cartoon**, is an animated film, usually a short film, that features an exaggerated style.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This style is often inspired by comic strips, gag cartoons, and other non-animated art forms.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Cartoons frequently include anthropomorphic animals, superheroes, or the adventures of human protagonists.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The action often revolves around exaggerated physical humor, particularly in predator and prey dynamics (e.g. cats and mice, coyotes and birds), where violent pratfalls such as falls, collisions, and explosions occur, often in ways that would be lethal in the real life.
[src:framer-motion/animation] During the late 1980s, the term "cartoon" was shortened to ***toon***, referring to characters in animated productions, or more specifically, cartoonishly-drawn characters.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This term gained popularity first in 1988 with the live-action/animated hybrid film *Who Framed Roger Rabbit*, which introduced ToonTown, a world inhabited by various animated cartoon characters.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 1990, *Tiny Toon Adventures* embraced the classic cartoon spirit, introducing a new generation of cartoon characters.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Then, in 1993, *Animaniacs* followed, featuring the three rubber-hose-styled Warner siblings, Yakko, Wakko, and Dot, who are trapped in the 1930s, eventually escaped and found themselves in the Warner Bros. water tower in the 1990s.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The illusion of animation—as in motion pictures in general—has traditionally been attributed to the persistence of vision and later to the phi phenomenon and beta movement, but the exact neurological causes are still uncertain.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The illusion of motion caused by a rapid succession of images that minimally differ from each other, with unnoticeable interruptions, is a stroboscopic effect.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Analog mechanical animation media that rely on the rapid display of sequential images include the phenakistiscope, zoetrope, flip book, praxinoscope, and film.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Television and video are popular electronic animation media that originally were analog and now operate digitally.
[src:framer-motion/animation] For display on computers, technology such as the animated GIF and Flash animation were developed.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In addition to short films, feature films, television series, animated GIFs, and other media dedicated to the display of moving images, animation is also prevalent in video games, motion graphics, user interfaces, and visual effects.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The physical movement of image parts through simple mechanics—for instance, moving images in magic lantern shows—can also be considered animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The mechanical manipulation of three-dimensional puppets and objects to emulate living beings has a very long history in automata.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Electronic automata were popularized by Disney as animatronics.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The word *animation* comes from the Latin word *animātiō*, meaning 'bestowing of life'.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The earlier meaning of the English word is 'liveliness' and has been in use much longer than the meaning of 'moving image medium'.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Long before modern animation began, audiences around the world were captivated by the magic of moving characters.
[src:framer-motion/animation] For centuries, master artists and craftsmen have brought puppets, automatons, shadow puppets, and fantastical lanterns to life, inspiring the imagination through physically manipulated wonders.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 1832, the phenakistoscope, invented by Belgian Joseph Plateau, would introduce the principle of modern animation, the principle of persistence of vision.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The principle would be later applied by William George Horner's zoetrope (1876), the flip book (1868), the praxinoscope(1877), and film.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The device was operated by spinning the cardboard disc and viewing the reflection of the image in a mirror through a series of moving slits, which created the illusion that the image was moving.Similarly, the zoetrope was operated by spinning a rotating drum lined up with a strip of pictures inside.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 1876, animation would be adapted for the theatrical audience, as entrepreneurs such as Emile Reynaud began investing in the art form.
[src:framer-motion/animation] It wasn't until the invention of sprocket-drive film stock, would animation begin to gain traction in cinema.
[src:framer-motion/animation] When cinematography eventually broke through in the 1890s, the wonder of the realistic details in the new medium was seen as its biggest accomplishment.
[src:framer-motion/animation] It took years before animation found its way to the cinemas.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The successful short *The Haunted Hotel* (1907) by J.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Stuart Blackton popularized stop motion and reportedly inspired Émile Cohl to create *Fantasmagorie* (1908), regarded as the oldest known example of a complete traditional (hand-drawn) animation on standard cinematographic film.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Other great artistic and very influential short films were created by Ladislas Starevich with his puppet animations since 1910 and by Winsor McCay with detailed hand-drawn animation in films such as *Little Nemo* (1911) and *Gertie the Dinosaur* (1914).
[src:framer-motion/animation] During the 1910s, the production of animated "cartoons" became an industry in the US.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Successful producer John Randolph Bray and animator Earl Hurd patented the cel animation process that dominated the animation industry for the rest of the century.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Felix the Cat, who debuted in 1919, became the first fully realized anthropomorphic animal character in the history of American animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The characteristics of Felix the cat's physical appearance would come to be the standard model for cartoon character in the following years.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 1928, *Steamboat Willie*, featuring Mickey Mouse and Minnie Mouse, popularized film-with-synchronized-sound and put Walt Disney's studio at the forefront of the animation industry.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Although Disney Animation's actual output relative to total global animation output has always been very small, the studio has overwhelmingly dominated the "aesthetic norms" of animation ever since.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The enormous success of Mickey Mouse is seen as the start of the golden age of American animation that would last until the 1960s.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The United States dominated the world market of animation with a plethora of cel-animated theatrical shorts.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Coyote and the Road Runner (1949), MGM cartoon studio's Tom and Jerry (1940) and Droopy, Universal Cartoon Studios' Woody Woodpecker (1940), Terrytoons/20th Century Fox's Mighty Mouse (1942), and United Artists' Pink Panther (1963).
[src:framer-motion/animation] After working on it for three years, Lotte Reiniger released the German feature-length silhouette animation *Die Abenteuer des Prinzen Achmed* in 1926, the oldest extant animated feature.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 1917, Italian-Argentine director Quirino Cristiani made the first feature-length film *El Apóstol* (now lost), which became a critical and commercial success.
[src:framer-motion/animation] It was followed by Cristiani's *Sin dejar rastros* in 1918, but one day after its premiere, the film was confiscated by the government.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 1937, Walt Disney Studios premiered their first animated feature *Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs*, still one of the highest-grossing traditional animation features as of May 2020.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The Fleischer studios followed this example in 1939 with *Gulliver's Travels* with some success.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Partly due to foreign markets being cut off by the Second World War, Disney's next features *Pinocchio*, *Fantasia* (both 1940), Fleischer Studios' second animated feature *Mr.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Bug Goes to Town* (1941–1942) failed at the box office.
[src:framer-motion/animation] For several decades, Disney was the only American studio to regularly produce animated features, until Ralph Bakshi became the first to release more than a handful of features.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Sullivan-Bluth Studios began to regularly produce animated features starting with *An American Tail* in 1986.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Although relatively few titles became as successful as Disney's features, other countries developed their own animation industries that produced both short and feature theatrical animations in a wide variety of styles, relatively often including stop motion and cutout animation techniques.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Soviet Soyuzmultfilm animation studio, founded in 1936, produced 20 films (including shorts) per year on average and reached 1,582 titles in 2018.
[src:framer-motion/animation] China, Czechoslovakia / Czech Republic, Italy, France, and Belgium were other countries that more than occasionally released feature films.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Animation became very popular on television since the 1950s, when television sets started to become common in most developed countries.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Cartoons were mainly programmed for children, on convenient time slots, and especially US youth spent many hours watching Saturday-morning cartoons.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Many classic cartoons found a new life on the small screen and by the end of the 1950s, the production of new animated cartoons started to shift from theatrical releases to TV series.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Hanna-Barbera Productions was especially prolific and had huge hit series, such as *The Flintstones* (1960–1966) (the first prime time animated series), *Scooby-Doo* (since 1969) and Belgian co-production *The Smurfs* (1981–1989).
[src:framer-motion/animation] The constraints of American television programming and the demand for an enormous quantity resulted in cheaper and quicker limited animation methods and much more formulaic scripts.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Quality dwindled until more daring animation surfaced in the late 1980s and in the early 1990s with hit series, the first cartoon of The Simpsons (1987), which later developed into its own show (in 1989) and *SpongeBob SquarePants* (since 1999) as part of a "renaissance" of American animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] While US animated series also spawned successes internationally, many other countries produced their own child-oriented programming, relatively often preferring stop motion and puppetry over cel animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Computer animation was gradually developed since the 1940s.
[src:framer-motion/animation] 3D wireframe animation started popping up in the mainstream in the 1970s, with an early (short) appearance in the sci-fi thriller *Futureworld* (1976).
[src:framer-motion/animation] The so-called 3D style, more often associated with computer animation, became the dominant technique following the success of Pixar's *Toy Story* (1995), the first computer-animated feature in this style.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Most of the cel animation studios switched to producing mostly computer-animated films around the 1990s, as it proved cheaper and more profitable.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 2010, the animation market was estimated to be worth circa US$80 billion.
[src:framer-motion/animation] By 2021, the value had increased to an estimated US$370 billion.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Animated feature-length films returned the highest gross margins (around 52%) of all film genres between 2004 and 2013.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Animation as an art and industry continues to thrive as of the early 2020s.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The clarity of animation makes it a powerful tool for instruction, while its total malleability also allows exaggeration that can be employed to convey strong emotions and to thwart reality.
[src:framer-motion/animation] It has therefore been widely used for other purposes than mere entertainment.
[src:framer-motion/animation] During World War II, animation was widely exploited for propaganda.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Many American studios, including Warner Bros. and Disney, lent their talents and their cartoon characters to convey to the public certain war values.
[src:framer-motion/animation] These efforts extended to other countries well into the Cold War era, particularly as it pertained to "combatting" communism.
[src:framer-motion/animation] For example, the English 1954 adaptation of George Orwell's *Animal Farm* (the nation's first feature-length animated film) is speculated to have had its production funded by the CIA.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Animation has been very popular in television commercials, both due to its graphic appeal, and the humour it can provide.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Some animated characters in commercials have survived for decades, such as Snap, Crackle and Pop in advertisements for Kellogg's cereals.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Tex Avery was the producer of the first Raid "Kills Bugs Dead" commercials in 1966, which were very successful for the company.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Apart from their success in movie theatres and television series, many cartoon characters would also prove lucrative when licensed for all kinds of merchandise and for other media.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Animation has traditionally been very closely related to comic books.
[src:framer-motion/animation] While many comic book characters found their way to the screen (which is often the case in Japan, where many manga are adapted into anime), original animated characters also commonly appear in comic books and magazines.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Somewhat similarly, characters and plots for video games (an interactive form of animation that became its own medium) have been derived from films and vice versa.
[src:framer-motion/animation] While very many animation companies commercially exploit their creations outside moving image media, The Walt Disney Company is the best known and most extreme example.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Since first being licensed for a children's writing tablet in 1929, their Mickey Mouse mascot has been depicted on an enormous amount of products, as have many other Disney characters.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This may have influenced some pejorative use of Mickey's name, but licensed Disney products sell well, and the so-called Disneyana has many avid collectors, and even a dedicated Disneyana Fan Club (since 1984).
[src:framer-motion/animation] Disneyland opened in 1955 and features many attractions that were based on Disney's cartoon characters.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Its enormous success spawned several other Disney theme parks and resorts.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Disney's earnings from the theme parks have relatively often been higher than those from their movies.
[src:framer-motion/animation] As with any other form of media, animation has instituted awards for excellence in the field.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Many are part of general or regional film award programs, like the China's Golden Rooster Award for Best Animation (since 1981).
[src:framer-motion/animation] Awards programs dedicated to animation, with many categories, include ASIFA-Hollywood's Annie Awards, the Emile Awards in Europe and the Anima Mundi awards in Brazil.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Apart from Academy Awards for Best Animated Short Film (since 1932) and Best Animated Feature (since 2002), animated movies have been nominated and rewarded in other categories, relatively often for Best Original Song and Best Original Score.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The creation of non-trivial animation works (i.e., longer than a few seconds) has developed as a form of filmmaking, with certain unique aspects.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Traits common to both live-action and animated feature films are labour intensity and high production costs.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The most important difference is that once a film is in the production phase, the marginal cost of one more shot is higher for animated films than live-action films.
[src:framer-motion/animation] It is pointless for a studio to pay the salaries of dozens of animators to spend weeks creating a visually dazzling five-minute scene if that scene fails to effectively advance the plot of the film.
[src:framer-motion/animation] While live-action films are now also storyboarded, they enjoy more latitude to depart from storyboards (i.e., real-time improvisation).
[src:framer-motion/animation] Another problem unique to animation is the requirement to maintain a film's consistency from start to finish, even as films have grown longer and teams have grown larger.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Animators, like all artists, necessarily have individual styles, but must subordinate their individuality in a consistent way to whatever style is employed on a particular film.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Since the early 1980s, teams of about 500 to 600 people, of whom 50 to 70 are animators, typically have created feature-length animated films.
[src:framer-motion/animation] It is relatively easy for two or three artists to match their styles; synchronizing those of dozens of artists is more difficult.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This problem is usually solved by having a separate group of visual development artists develop an overall look and palette for each film before the animation begins.
[src:framer-motion/animation] While animators must "sacrifice their personal drawing styles so that the work of many hands appears to be that of one", visual development artists are allowed to "create new worlds, new characters, and new entertainment possibilities in their own individualistic graphic styles".
[src:framer-motion/animation] Character designers on the visual development team draw model sheets to show how each character should look with different facial expressions, posed in different positions, and viewed from different angles.
[src:framer-motion/animation] On traditionally animated projects, maquettes were often sculpted to further help the animators see how characters would look from different angles.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Unlike live-action films, animated films were traditionally developed beyond the synopsis stage through the storyboard format; the storyboard artists would then receive credit for writing the film.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The traditional approach worked for several decades because prior to the 1960s, no one except Disney was attempting to regularly produce feature-length animated films.
[src:framer-motion/animation] All other animation studios, with occasional exceptions, were producing short films only a few minutes in length.
[src:framer-motion/animation] For short films, it was enough for the storyboard artists to work up a few visual gags and then string them together to form a crude plot.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In 1960, Hanna-Barbera pioneered the longer animated sitcom format for television with *The Flintstones*.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Hanna-Barbera and the other early television animation studios soon discovered that storyboarding was far too inefficient to fill up a half-hour episode on the extremely tight budgets typical of television.
[src:framer-motion/animation] During the 1960s, these studios experimented with a more efficient method for developing story material: a screenwriter is hired to draft a written screenplay which is approved and handed over to the storyboard artists for storyboarding.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This method creates significant tension between screenwriters and storyboard artists, in that some artists feel that people who cannot draw should not be writing for animation, while some writers feel that artists do not understand how to write.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Despite that tension, it has become and remains the dominant method by which animation studios develop both feature-length films and television shows.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Ironically, the Disney studio was relatively slow to adopt this method.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The first Disney feature animated film to have a complete screenplay written and approved before storyboarding was *One Hundred and One Dalmatians* (1961).
[src:framer-motion/animation] However, *101 Dalmatians* was "a short-lived experiment"; the next Disney film to follow this method was *The Great Mouse Detective* (1986).
[src:framer-motion/animation] Finally, another key difference is that actors traditionally record vocal tracks for animated films in separate individual sessions; they often meet one another for the first time only at the film's premiere.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Actors usually schedule sessions in the recording studio around their live-action work.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The traditional cel animation process became obsolete by the beginning of the 21st century.
[src:framer-motion/animation] In modern traditionally animated films, animators' drawings and the backgrounds are either scanned into or drawn directly into a computer system.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Various software programs are used to colour the drawings and simulate camera movement and effects.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The final animated piece is output to one of several delivery media, including traditional 35 mm film and newer media with digital video.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The "look" of traditional cel animation is still preserved, and the character animators' work has remained essentially the same over the past 90 years.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Some animation producers have used the term "tradigital" (a play on the words "traditional" and "digital") to describe cel animation that uses significant computer technology.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Examples of traditionally animated feature films include *Pinocchio* (United States, 1940), *Animal Farm* (United Kingdom, 1954), *Lucky and Zorba* (Italy, 1998), and *The Illusionist* (British-French, 2010).
[src:framer-motion/animation] Stop motion is used to describe animation created by physically manipulating real-world objects and photographing them one frame of film at a time to create the illusion of movement.
[src:framer-motion/animation] There are many different types of stop-motion animation, usually named after the materials used to create the animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Computer software is widely available to create this type of animation; traditional stop-motion animation is usually less expensive but more time-consuming to produce than current computer animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Typically involves stop-motion puppet figures interacting in a constructed environment, in contrast to real-world interaction in model animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] inside of them to keep them still and steady to constrain their motion to particular joints.
[src:framer-motion/animation] are puppet-animated films that typically use a different version of a puppet for different frames, rather than manipulating one existing puppet.
[src:framer-motion/animation] It uses figures made of clay or a similar malleable material to create stop-motion animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] or wire frame inside, similar to the related puppet animation (below), that can be manipulated to pose the figures.
[src:framer-motion/animation] , where clay creatures morph into a variety of different shapes.
[src:framer-motion/animation] (Sometimes called paper animation) A type of stop-motion animation produced by moving two-dimensional pieces of material paper or cloth.
[src:framer-motion/animation] (US, 1997) and the music video Live for the moment, from Verona Riots band (produced by Alberto Serrano and Nívola Uyá, Spain 2014).
[src:framer-motion/animation] A variant of cutout animation in which the characters are backlit and only visible as silhouettes.
[src:framer-motion/animation] by doing cutting, folding, gluing and assembling.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Stop-motion animation created to interact with and exist as a part of a live-action world.
[src:framer-motion/animation] effects and split screens are often employed to blend stop-motion characters or objects with live actors and settings.
[src:framer-motion/animation] between frames of film, which is not present in traditional stop motion.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The use of regular inanimate objects in stop-motion animation, as opposed to specially created items.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Uses non-drawn flat visual graphic material (photographs, newspaper clippings, magazines, etc.), which are sometimes manipulated frame by frame to create movement.
[src:framer-motion/animation] At other times, the graphics remain stationary, while the stop-motion camera is moved to create on-screen action.
[src:framer-motion/animation] or other similar brick toys to make an animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Involves the use of live humans as stop-motion characters.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This allows for a number of surreal effects, including disappearances and reappearances, allowing people to appear to slide across the ground, and other effects.
[src:framer-motion/animation] 2D animation figures are created or edited on the computer using 2D bitmap graphics and 2D vector graphics.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This includes automated computerized versions of traditional animation techniques, interpolated morphing, onion skinning and interpolated rotoscoping.
[src:framer-motion/animation] 2D animation has many applications, including After Effects Animation, analog computer animation, Flash animation, and PowerPoint animation.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Cinemagraphs are still photographs in the form of an animated GIF file of which part is animated.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Final line advection animation is a technique used in 2D animation, to give artists and animators more influence and control over the final product as everything is done within the same department.
[src:framer-motion/animation] When working with game animations, skeletal 2D animations are commonly created using tools like Spine, DragonBones, Blender COA Tools, Rive, and the built-in Unity editor.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The primary benefit of this approach is the ability to reuse images, which reduces the amount of graphics stored in RAM.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This principle of maximizing resource efficiency means that by reusing existing elements, you can enhance the visual appeal of animations without needing to create additional graphics.
[src:framer-motion/animation] 3D animation is digitally modelled and manipulated by an animator.
[src:framer-motion/animation] The 3D model maker usually starts by creating a 3D polygon mesh for the animator to manipulate.
[src:framer-motion/animation] A mesh typically includes many vertices that are connected by edges and faces, which give the visual appearance of form to a 3D object or 3D environment.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Sometimes, the mesh is given an internal digital skeletal structure called an armature that can be used to control the mesh by weighting the vertices.
[src:framer-motion/animation] This process is called rigging and can be used in conjunction with key frames to create movement.
[src:framer-motion/animation] Other techniques can be applied, mathematical functions (e.g., gravity, particle simulations), simulated fur or hair, and effects, fire and water simulations.
[src:framer-motion/animation] These techniques fall under the category of 3D dynamics.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] It’s been available across browsers since September 2015.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] The **`transform`** CSS property lets you rotate, scale, skew, or translate an element.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] It modifies the coordinate space of the CSS visual formatting model.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] If the property has a value different from `none`, a stacking context will be created.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] In that case, the element will act as a containing block for any `position: fixed;` or `position: absolute;` elements that it contains.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] You can also use the individual transform properties: `translate`, `rotate`, and `scale`.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] These properties are applied in the order: `translate`, `rotate`, `scale`, and finally `transform`.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] The `transform` property may be specified as either the keyword value `none` or as one or more `<transform-function>` values.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] One or more of the CSS transform functions to be applied.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] The transform functions are combined from left to right – each function establishes a new coordinate space for the next function and so on – so the visual result matches the written order of the functions.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] Alternatively, keeping the parent coordinate space fixed, the same transformation can be described as applying the functions in reverse order (right to left).
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] Specifies that no transform should be applied.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] Scaling/zooming animations are problematic for accessibility, as they are a common trigger for certain types of migraine.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] If you need to include such animations on your website, you should provide a control to allow users to turn off animations, preferably site-wide.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] Also, consider making use of the `prefers-reduced-motion` media feature — use it to write a media query that will turn off animations if the user has reduced animation specified in their system preferences.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] The order of transform functions matters.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] In this example, two boxes are rotated and translated by the same values, but the functions are in the opposite order.
[src:framer-motion/css-transform] The dotted lines mark the X-axis before and after rotation.
[src:framer-motion/framer-motion] Motion is available for React, JavaScript and Vue.
[src:framer-motion/framer-motion] Browse 330+ official examples, with copy-paste code that'll level-up your animations whether you're a beginner or an expert.
[src:framer-motion/framer-motion] Over 100 examples come with a full step-by-step tutorial.
[src:framer-motion/framer-motion] Motion is sustainable thanks to the kind support of its sponsors.
[src:framer-motion/framer-motion] Motion powers the animations for all websites built with Framer, the web builder for creative pros.
[src:framer-motion/framer-motion] The Motion website itself is built on Framer, for its delightful canvas-based editing and powerful CMS features.
[src:framer-motion/framer-motion] Motion drives the animations on the Cursor homepage, and is working with Cursor to bring powerful AI workflows to the Motion examples and docs.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:framer-motion/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Since there is no universally accepted definition of motion graphics, the official beginning of the art form is disputed.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] There have been presentations that could be classified as motion graphics as early as the 19th century.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Michael Betancourt wrote the first in-depth historical survey of the field, arguing for its foundations in visual music and the historical abstract films of the 1920s by Walther Ruttmann, Hans Richter, Viking Eggeling and Oskar Fischinger.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] The history of motion graphics is closely related to the history of computer graphics, as the new developments of computer-generated graphics led to wider use of motion design not based on optical film animation.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] The term motion graphics originated with digital video editing in computing, perhaps to keep pace with newer technology.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Graphics for television were originally referred to as Broadcast Design.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Walter Ruttmann was a German cinematographer and film director who worked mainly in experimental film.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] The films were experiments in new forms of film expression and featured shapes of different colors flowing back and forth and in and out of the lens.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] He started his film career in the early 1920s, starting with abstract films Lichtspiel: Opus I (1921), the first publicly screened abstract film, and Opus II (1923.) The animations were painted with oil on glass plates, so the wet paint could be wiped away and modified easily.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] John Whitney was of the first users of the term "motion graphics" and founded a company called Motion Graphics Inc. in 1960.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] One of his most famous works was the animated title sequence from Alfred Hitchcock’s film “Vertigo” in 1958, collaborating with Saul Bass, which featured swirling graphics growing from small to large.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Saul Bass was a major pioneer in the development of feature film title sequences.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] His work included title sequences for popular films such as *The Man with the Golden Arm* (1955), *Vertigo* (1958), *Anatomy of a Murder* (1959), *North by Northwest* (1959), *Psycho* (1960), and *Advise & Consent* (1962).
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] His designs were simple, but effectively communicated the mood of the film.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Stan Brakhage was one of the most important figures in 20th-century experimental film.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] He explored a variety of formats, creating a large, diverse body of work.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] His influence in the credits of the film Seven (1995), designed by Kyle Cooper, with the scratched emulsion, rapid cutaways, and bursts of light in his style.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Before computers were widely available, motion graphics were costly and time-consuming, limiting their use to high-budget filmmaking and television production.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Computers began to be used as early as the late 1960s as super computers were capable of rendering crude graphics.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] John Whitney and Charles Csuri can be considered early pioneers of computer aided animation.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] In the late 1980s to mid-1990s, expensive proprietary graphics systems such as those from British-based Quantel were quite commonplace in many television stations.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Quantel workstations such as the Hal, Henry, Harry, Mirage, and Paintbox were the broadcast graphics standard of the time.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Many other real-time graphics systems were used such as Ampex ADO, Abekas A51 and Grass Valley Group Kaleidoscope for live digital video effects.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Early proprietary 3D computer systems were also developed specifically for broadcast design such as the Bosch FGS-4000 which was used in the music video for Dire Straits' Money for Nothing.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] The advent of more powerful desktop computers running Photoshop in the mid-90s drastically lowered the costs for producing digital graphics.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] With the reduced cost of producing motion graphics on a computer, the discipline has seen more widespread use.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] With the availability of desktop programs such as Adobe After Effects, Adobe Premiere Pro and Apple Motion, motion graphics have become increasingly accessible.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Modern character generators (CG) from Vizrt and Ross Video, incorporate motion graphics.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Motion graphics continued to evolve as an art form with the incorporation of sweeping camera paths and 3D elements.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Maxon's Cinema 4D, plugins such as MoGraph and Adobe After Effects.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Despite their relative complexity, Autodesk's Maya and 3D Studio Max are widely used for the animation and design of motion graphics, as is Maya and 3D Studio which uses a node-based particle system generator similar to Cinema 4D's Thinking Particles plugin.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] There are also some other packages in Open Source panorama, which are gaining more features and adepts in order to use in a motion graphics workflow, while Blender integrates several of the functions of its commercial counterparts.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Many motion graphics animators learn several 3D graphics packages for use according to each program's strengths.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Although many trends in motion graphics tend to be based on a specific software's capabilities, the software is only a tool the broadcast designer uses while bringing the vision to life.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Leaning heavily from techniques such as the collage or the pastiche, motion graphics have begun to integrate many traditional animation techniques as well, including stop-motion animation, frame by frame animation, or a combination of both.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Motion design applications include Adobe After Effects, Blackmagic Fusion, Nuke, Apple Motion, Max/MSP, various VJ programs, Moho, Adobe Animate, Natron.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] 3D programs used in motion graphics include Adobe Substance, Maxon Cinema 4D and Blender.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Motion graphics plug-ins include Video Copilot's products, Red Giant Software and The Foundry Visionmongers.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Elements of a motion graphics project can be animated by various means, depending on the capabilities of the software.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] These elements may be in the form of art, text, photos, and video clips, to name a few.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] The most popular form of animation is keyframing, in which properties of an object can be specified at certain points in time by setting a series of keyframes so that the properties of the object can be automatically altered (or tweened) in the frames between keyframes.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Another method involves a behavior system such as is found in Apple Motion that controls these changes by simulating natural forces without requiring the more rigid but precise keyframing method.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Yet another method involves the use of formulas or scripts, such as the expressions function in Adobe After Effects or the creation of ActionScripts within Adobe Flash.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Computers are capable of calculating and randomizing changes in imagery to create the illusion of motion and transformation.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Computer animations can use less information space (computer memory) by automatically tweening, a process of rendering the key changes of an image at a specified or calculated time.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] These key poses or frames are commonly referred to as keyframes or low CP.
[src:framer-motion/motion-graphics] Adobe Flash uses computer animation tweening as well as frame-by-frame animation and video.
[src:framer-motion/page] Reference for Motion across React, JavaScript, and Vue, plus our Motion developer tools.
[src:framer-motion/page] Features live examples and copy-paste snippets for every API.
[src:framer-motion/page] Unlock 400+ premium examples, premium APIs, private Discord and GitHub, and a transition editor for your IDE.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] The **Web Animations API** allows for synchronizing and timing changes to the presentation of a Web page, i.e., animation of DOM elements.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] It does so by combining two models: the Timing Model and the Animation Model.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] The Web Animations API provides a common language for browsers and developers to describe animations on DOM elements.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] To get more information on the concepts behind the API and how to use it, read Using the Web Animations API.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] Provides playback controls and a timeline for an animation node or source.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] Can take an object created with the `KeyframeEffect()` constructor.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] Describes sets of animatable properties and values, called **keyframes** and their timing options.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] These can then be played using the `Animation()` constructor.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] This interface exists to define timeline features (inherited by `DocumentTimeline` and future timeline objects) and is not itself accessed by developers.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] Part of the CSS Animations module, capturing the animation name and elapsed time.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] Represents animation timelines, including the default document timeline (accessed using the `Document.timeline` property).
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] The Web Animations API adds features to `document` and `element`.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] The `DocumentTimeline` object representing the default document timeline.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] Returns an Array of `Animation` objects currently in effect on elements in the `document`.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] A shortcut method for creating and playing an animation on an element.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] It returns the created `Animation` object instance.
[src:framer-motion/web-animations-api] Returns an Array of `Animation` objects currently affecting an element or which are scheduled to do so in the future.
